ricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection investigates the concept of modernity in music and its multiple interpretations in Europe and Asia. Through contributions by both European and Asian musicologists it discusses how a decentered understanding of musical modernity could be matched on multiple historiographical perspectives while attentive to the specificities of local music and their narratives in Asia and Europe. The essays connect local, global and transnational history with sociological theories of modernity and modernization, making the volume an important contribution to overcoming the Eurocentric dichotomy between western music and world music within the field of historical musicology.  afunded by Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (DFG)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCivilization, Modern, in music. 0aModernism (Music) 0aMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszAsia. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszEurope. 0aMusicy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiczEast AsiaxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiczEast AsiaxWestern influences. 0aMusiczEast Asiay20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPostcolonialismzEast Asia. 4aAsia. 4aCultural History. 4aGlobal History. 4aModernity. 4aMusic History. 4aMusicology. 4aPostcolonialism. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAsia.  aCultural History.  aGlobal History.  aModernity.  aMusic History.  aMusicology.  aPostcolonialism.1 aChien-Chang, Yang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFumitaka, Yamauchi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHsin-Wen, Hsu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanz, Tobias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v